    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Gr95] Granville, Andrew, Harald {C}ram\\'{e}r and the distribution of prime numbers. Scand. Actuar. J. (1995), 12--28.",
      "remarks": "This follows from 'plausible assumptions on the distribution of primes' (as does the question with $k^2$ replaced by $k^d$ for any $d$); the challenge is to prove this unconditionally.\n\nErd\\H{o}s observed that Cramer's conjecture\\[\\limsup_{k\\to \\infty} \\frac{p_{k+1}-p_k}{(\\log k)^2}=1\\]implies that for all $\\epsilon>0$ and all sufficiently large $n$ there exists some $k$ such that\\[p(n+k)>e^{(1-\\epsilon)\\sqrt{k}}.\\]There is now evidence, however, that Cramer's conjecture is false; a more refined heuristic by Granville \\cite{Gr95} suggests this $\\limsup$ is $2e^{-\\gamma}\\approx 1.119\\cdots$, and so perhaps the $1+\\epsilon$ in the second question should be replaced by $2e^{-\\gamma}+\\epsilon$.\n\nSee also [681] and [682]."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "number theory",
      "primes"
    ]
  },
